{"parse":{"title":"Weyl sequence","pageid":56841538,"revid":859270392,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Mathematics\" title=\"Mathematics\">mathematics</a>, a <b>Weyl sequence</b> is a sequence from the <a href=\"/wiki/Equidistribution_theorem\" title=\"Equidistribution theorem\">equidistribution theorem</a> proven by <a href=\"/wiki/Hermann_Weyl\" title=\"Hermann Weyl\">Hermann Weyl</a>:<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>\n</p><p>The sequence of all multiples of an irrational <i>\u03b1</i>,\n</p>\n<dl><dd><dl><dd>0, <i>\u03b1</i>, 2<i>\u03b1</i>, 3<i>\u03b1</i>, 4<i>\u03b1</i>, ...</dd></dl></dd>\n<dd>is <a href=\"/wiki/Continuous_uniform_distribution\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Continuous uniform distribution\">equidistributed</a> modulo 1.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup></dd></dl>\n<p>In other words, the sequence of the fractional parts of each term will be uniformly distributed in the interval&#160;[0,&#160;1).\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"In_computing\">In computing</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Weyl_sequence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: In computing\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>In <a href=\"/wiki/Computing\" title=\"Computing\">computing</a>, an integer version of this sequence is often used to generate a <a href=\"/wiki/Discrete_uniform_distribution\" title=\"Discrete uniform distribution\">discrete uniform distribution</a> rather than a continuous one.   Instead of using an irrational number, which cannot be calculated on a digital computer, the ratio of two integers is used in its place.  An integer <i>k</i> is chosen, <a href=\"/wiki/Relatively_prime\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Relatively prime\">relatively prime</a> to an integer modulus <i>m</i>.  In the common case that <i>m</i> is a power of 2, this amounts to requiring that <i>k</i> is odd.\n</p><p>The sequence of all multiples of such an integer integer&#160;<i>k</i>,\n</p>\n<dl><dd><dl><dd>0, <i>k</i>, 2<i>k</i>, 3<i>k</i>, 4<i>k</i>, \u2026</dd></dl></dd>\n<dd>is equidistributed modulo <i>m</i>.</dd></dl>\n<p>That is, the sequence of the remainders of each term when divided by <i>m</i> will be uniformly distributed in the interval <span class=\"nowrap\">[0, <i>m</i></span>).\n</p><p>The term appears to originate with <a href=\"/wiki/George_Marsaglia\" title=\"George Marsaglia\">George Marsaglia</a>\u2019s paper <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"http://www.jstatsoft.org/v08/i14/paper\">\"Xorshift RNGs\"</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-marsaglia_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-marsaglia-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> \nThe following C code generates what Marsaglia calls a \"Weyl sequence\":\n</p>\n<dl><dd><dl><dd>d += 362437;</dd></dl></dd></dl>\n<p>In this case, the odd integer is 362437, and the results are computed modulo <span class=\"nowrap\"><i>m</i> = 2<sup><i>32</i></sup></span> because d is a 32-bit quantity. The results are equidistributed modulo 2<sup>32</sup>.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"See_also\">See also</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Weyl_sequence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: See also\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a href=\"/wiki/List_of_things_named_after_Hermann_Weyl\" title=\"List of things named after Hermann Weyl\">List of things named after Hermann Weyl</a></li></ul>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Weyl_sequence&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\"><a href=\"/wiki/Hermann_Weyl\" title=\"Hermann Weyl\">Weyl, H.</a> (September 1916). \"\u00dcber die Gleichverteilung von Zahlen mod. Eins\" &#91;On the uniform distribution of numbers modulo one&#93;. <i>Mathematische Annalen</i> (in German). <b>77</b> (3): 313\u2013352. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.1007/BF01475864\">10.1007/BF01475864</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=Mathematische+Annalen&amp;rft.atitle=%C3%9Cber+die+Gleichverteilung+von+Zahlen+mod.+Eins&amp;rft.volume=77&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=313-352&amp;rft.date=1916-09&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1007%2FBF01475864&amp;rft.aulast=Weyl&amp;rft.aufirst=H.&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3AWeyl+sequence\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation book\">Kuipers, L.; <a href=\"/wiki/Harald_Niederreiter\" title=\"Harald Niederreiter\">Niederreiter, H.</a> (2006) [1974]. <i>Uniform Distribution of Sequences</i>. Dover Publications. <a href=\"/wiki/International_Standard_Book_Number\" title=\"International Standard Book Number\">ISBN</a>&#160;<a href=\"/wiki/Special:BookSources/0-486-45019-8\" title=\"Special:BookSources/0-486-45019-8\">0-486-45019-8</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Abook&amp;rft.genre=book&amp;rft.btitle=Uniform+Distribution+of+Sequences&amp;rft.pu